Premium Play - or Hybrid Cyclical?
Key: Historical Stock Performance Current Stock Price Price Target

In principle, the de- rating process has played out, and we are more optimistic than many around a recovery in activity levels in China Rail. Nonetheless, investor confidence has been heavily dented over the last two years, and the ultimate path that Knorr Bremse will take strategically remains an open question. The upside case for the shares could come from a period of management stability, earnings recovery and a re- rating back toward premium Capital Goods multiples. The downside risk is that the premium has gone now, and Knorr Bremse will simply trade like other diversified engineering suppliers.
Consensus Rating Distribution
Source: Refinitiv, Morgan Stanley Research

All figures are approximate risk- neutral probabilities of the stock reaching beyond the scenario price in either three- months' or one- years' time. View explanation of Options Probabilities methodology here

In our bull case, we assume a high- single- digit sales increase YoY 2026 with \(10\%\) growth in rail and a MSD% development in trucks (high- single- digit organic more than offset M&A effect). The group EBITDA margin rises 160bps YoY to \(19.2\%\) as both divisions benefit from higher volume. In this scenario, Knorr Bremse earns 5.51 EPS in FY26e.

We forecast mid- single- digit sales growth in 2026e, with MSD% organic growth in RVS and a LSD% growth in CVS. Group EBITDA margin is up 90bps YoY to \(18.4\%\) with RVS expanding 50bps and CVS bounces back strongly on better volume (after two soft years) and divestment of lower profitable businesses, expanding 130bps YoY. Knorr Bremse earns 4.87 EPS in FY26e.

We model 2026 sales to be down LSD% driven by continued decline of CVS (including negative M&A effect) and LSD% growth at RVS. The Group EBITDA margin is lower at \(17.0\%\) as CVS is impacted by negative organic growth. On these numbers, Knorr Bremse earns 4.04 EPS in 2026e.
Growth will be heavily influenced by rail dynamics, in China and other countries.
Truck markets may be more cyclical, but the group can benefit from greater regional penetration and content gains. Investments needed to drive further growth.
Source: Morgan Stanley Research Estimate View explanation of regional hierarchies here
Source: Refinitiv, FactSet, Morgan Stanley Research; 1 is the highest favored Quintile and 5 is the least favored Quintile
Higher investments than expected in rail infrastructure, and improvement in industrial activity leading to increasing demand for Trucks.
Competition from new- entrant players, especially in China Rail; global Truck demand cycles; unexpected and meaningful strategic changes.
